	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105034912024?origin=resultslist},
	abstract = {The rapid development of educational technology has transformed the way personalized and adaptive learning works. However, transforming complex mathematical concepts into accessible learning materials remains a significant challenge. This study introduces an adaptive learning platform that integrates machine learning models with didactic principles to improve students' algebra comprehension. The system uses clustering and recommendation mechanisms to analyze student performance and tailor learning content to their individual needs. The K-Means clustering algorithm is applied to group students into five categories based on conceptual understanding, reasoning clarity, analytical depth, cognitive level, and error propensity. Furthermore, the BERT model is used to evaluate students' written responses. This framework not only designs a personalized learning recommendation system for each student but is also designed to help teachers adapt their learning strategies to align with students' cognitive processes. The proposed design demonstrates how data-driven modeling can operationalize the concept of didactic transposition in a digital learning environment, making mathematics education more flexible, reflective, and conceptually grounded. Future work would focus on testing this system to evaluate its effectiveness in improving students' algebra comprehension and reducing common misconceptions. © 2025 IEEE.},
